<subSubSection type="nomenclature">
<paragraph pageNumber="248">
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:138864" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Ponera" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Ponera nitidula Emery" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="248" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nitidula">Ponera nitidula Emery</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="discussion">
<paragraph pageNumber="248">
Chiapas, soil. This is a handsome black ant displaying often quite brilliant satiny blue metallescence. A greasy specimen from Guatemala in the Wheeler Collection shows none of this blue reflection, and Emery did not mention it in the original description. The habitus is quite different from that of species like 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:138873" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Ponera" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Ponera opaciceps Mayr" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="248" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="opaciceps">Ponera opaciceps Mayr</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:228145" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Ponera" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Manual - Ponera trigona" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="248" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="trigona">Ponera trigona Mayr</taxonomicName>
, and it would not be surprising if 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:138864" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Ponera" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Ponera nitidula Emery" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="248" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nitidula">Ponera nitidula</taxonomicName>
were eventually shown to represent part of a distinct subgenus.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
